Anonymous Mon 27 Dec 2021 04:38:10 No.44256059 Report
Quoted By: >>44256234 >>44256352 >>44256653
>>44255230
>Any tips for how much overhead you'd need?
However much it takes to not abandon the story.
For what I'm finishing up, that's the whole thing. It couldn't have been done any other way.
What I want to restart? I've got the better part of two chapters (one day and the flashback chapter) done. I've got a solid outline, so I'm looking to be two to three days of storytime ahead. With that I can edit and have an inciting incident/stew over it/response pattern that feels natural.
Ive never written anything that went exactly by the plans I made. You write and learn how to think out your pacing/beats in advance. The last thing you want is a chapter that's whole purpose is to insert something that should have been in ten chapters back, or a 10k chapter that is devoted to a single, two sentence minor story beat.

On the other hand, that's how you also learn to write better dialogue and characters. Digging yourself out of a narrative hole isn't fun. Stories die because of it. But you're not going to learn all the mechanics without writing a lot, then stepping back and taking a few lumps.

Once you get to a point where you feel you have a handle on things, put out a call for beta readers and rubber duck with them. A good beta is going to force you to think by asking questions and/or reading critically.
That's yet another skill you develop, but anyone (yes, I say in my best carnival barker voice) can try their hand at beta reading.
I should write up my thoughts on that over the next few weeks. We have enough new blood here that could benefit from knowing that contributing doesn't always mean your name in the OP.

>That's my worry.
Then you're in good company. Just put a bit of your heart in it and have fun writing. None of what I said above was learned in a day or by advice.
The oldest parts of the masterbin are littered with stories where people just said, "Fuck it. I don't care if it's not good enough. It's the story I want to tell, and I'm damned well telling it."
